          "body": "The riot is Luke's coda. Demetrius the silversmith convenes the guild of shrine-makers with a candid speech (v. 25): *our prosperity depends upon this business*. The religious complaint about Artemis (v. 27) is pretext; the actual concern is the silver-shrine trade. Luke's anatomy of idolatry is devastating — paganism collapses when it cannot prove profitable. The crowd shouts *Great is Artemis of the Ephesians* for two hours (v. 34), accomplishing nothing. Luke's irony is unmistakable: pagan civic order, not Christian argument, defuses the crisis. The town clerk's pragmatic speech (vv. 35-40) protects Paul and admits, against his own intention, that the apostles *are neither robbers of temples nor blasphemers of our goddess* (v. 37) — Paul did not attack Artemis; he proclaimed Christ. The gospel does not need anti-pagan polemic. It needs the positive proclamation of the Lord Jesus, in whose presence the goddess is exposed as a silver-shrine trade dressed in cultic clothing."
